Answer: Here is a basic Maven `pom.xml` template for compiling a Java project:

```xml
<project xmlns="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
  xsi:schemaLocation="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0 http://maven.apache.org/xsd/maven-4.0.0.xsd">
    <modelVersion>4.0.0</modelVersion>

    <groupId>com.example</groupId>
    <artifactId>my-java-project</artifactId>
    <version>1.0-SNAPSHOT</version>
    <packaging>jar</packaging>

    <name>My Java Project</name>
    <description>This is my Java project.</description>

    <properties>
        <project.build.sourceEncoding>UTF-8</project.build.sourceEncoding>
        <maven.compiler.source>1.8</maven.compiler.source>
        <maven.compiler.target>1.8</maven.compiler.target>
    </properties>

    <dependencies>
        <!-- Add your dependencies here -->
    </dependencies>

    <build>
        <plugins>
            <plugin>
                <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>
                <artifactId>maven-compiler-plugin</artifactId>
                <version>3.8.1</version>
                <configuration>
                    <source>${maven.compiler.source}</source>
                    <target>${maven.compiler.target}</target>
                </configuration>
            </plugin>
        </plugins>
    </build>
</project>
```

To implement this system, the temperature sensor, such as the DS18B20 or LM35, can be connected to the Arduino board. The analog output pin of the temperature sensor is connected to the analog input pin of the Arduino board [[2](https://arduinogetstarted.com/tutorials/arduino-display-temperature-from-lm35-sensor-on-lcd)]. The LCD screen can be connected to the Arduino board using the LiquidCrystal I2C library [[1](https://arduinogetstarted.com/tutorials/arduino-temperature-sensor-lcd)].

The Arduino code can be written to read the temperature value from the temperature sensor, display it on the LCD screen, and adjust the brightness of the LCD screen based on the potentiometer value. The code can be uploaded to the Arduino board using the Arduino IDE.

In JavaScript, a case-sensitive sorting is the default behavior when sorting strings. However, if you want to perform a case-insensitive sorting, you can use the `localeCompare()` method or the `toLowerCase()`/`toUpperCase()` methods in conjunction with the `sort()` method. Here are a few examples:

**Using `localeCompare()`**
```javascript
const arr = ['Zebra', 'apple', 'Orange', 'banana'];
arr.sort((a, b) => a.localeCompare(b));
console.log(arr); // Output: ["apple", "banana", "Orange", "Zebra"]
```
**Using `toLowerCase()`**
```javascript
const arr = ['Zebra', 'apple', 'Orange', 'banana'];
arr.sort((a, b) => a.toLowerCase().localeCompare(b.toLowerCase()));
console.log(arr); // Output: ["apple", "banana", "Orange", "Zebra"]
```
**Using `toUpperCase()`**
```javascript
const arr = ['Zebra', 'apple', 'Orange', 'banana'];
arr.sort((a, b) => a.toUpperCase().localeCompare(b.toUpperCase()));
console.log(arr); // Output: ["apple", "banana", "Orange", "Zebra"]
```
Note that the `localeCompare()` method is more efficient and reliable than using `toLowerCase()` or `toUpperCase()` because it takes into account the locale-specific sorting rules.
